Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register your route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — string ID vs. full object:**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs — on item tapped

// Approach A: pass the ID as a simple query string
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B: pass the full object via dictionary
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", product }
});
```

**3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            string productId = idObj.ToString();
            // fetch product from service, etc.
            LoadProduct(productId);
        }

        // Approach B: full object (passed via dictionary overload)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj) 
            && productObj is Product product)
        {
            Name = product.Name;
            Price = product.Price;
            // use directly — no extra fetch needed
        }
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page:**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `$"route?key={val}"` | `GoToAsync(route, dict)` |
| **Arrives as** | `string` in the dictionary | Original typed object |
| **Use when** | Deep links, simple IDs | You already have the object in memory |

Both approaches funnel through the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can handle either (or both) in one place.
